"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"testing, effects management and dependency injection."}],"type":"topic","role":"overview","title":"Statoscope basics","kind":"overview"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-05-Scopes#Designing-Scopes":{"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"In complex applications, managing all state and events in a single Statostore quickly becomes unsustainable. To scale effectively, we need to split the app’s state and events into separate parts or Scopes. This process can sometimes be straightforward, but other times, developers may feel compelled to separate state and events that are closely tied together due to business logic. In this tutorial, we’ll focus on how to organize app state into different scopes to maintain scalability."}],"title":"Designing Scopes","type":"section","kind":"section","role":"pseudoSymbol","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-05-scopes#Designing-Scopes","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-05-Scopes#Designing-Scopes"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-03-Middleware":{"type":"topic","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-03-middleware","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-03-Middleware","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Understand how the single entry point enables pretty interesting features"}],"role":"project","estimatedTime":"30min","kind":"project","title":"Single entry point and\/or middlewares"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-05-Scopes#Views-and-Scopes":{"kind":"section","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"In complex applications, managing all state and events in a single Statostore quickly becomes unsustainable. To scale effectively, we need to split the app’s state and events into separate parts or Scopes. This process can sometimes be straightforward, but other times, developers may feel compelled to separate state and events that are closely tied together due to business logic. In this tutorial, we’ll focus on how to organize app state into different scopes to maintain scalability."}],"url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-05-scopes#Views-and-Scopes","role":"pseudoSymbol","identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-05-Scopes#Views-and-Scopes","title":"Views and Scopes","type":"section"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-01-StateAndWhen#Create-a-scope":{"type":"section","role":"pseudoSymbol","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Define a scope object with state member variables representing"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"a part of your app’s status, define the events that may affect","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"this state, and create a view to display the state.","type":"text"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-01-StateAndWhen#Create-a-scope","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-01-stateandwhen#Create-a-scope","kind":"section","title":"Create a scope"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-02-StateWhenAndEffects":{"type":"topic","role":"project","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Trigger effects that will get back to your scope as a new When event."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-02-StateWhenAndEffects","estimatedTime":"30min","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-02-statewhenandeffects","kind":"project","title":"State, When and Effects"},"01-03-01-code-0001.swift":{"fileType":"swift","fileName":"Counter.swift","type":"file","identifier":"01-03-01-code-0001.swift","content":["import Statoscope","","private final class Counter: Scope, ObservableObject {","","    @Published var viewDisplaysTotalCount: Int = 0","","    enum When {","        case userTappedIncrementButton","        case userTappedDecrementButton","    }","","    func update(_ when: When) throws {","        \/* ... *\/","    }","}"],"highlights":[],"syntax":"swift"},"01-03-01-code-0002.swift":{"fileName":"CounterView.swift","identifier":"01-03-01-code-0002.swift","fileType":"swift","highlights":[],"content":["import Statoscope","import SwiftUI","","private struct CounterView: View {","","    @StateObject var model = Counter()","","    var body: some View {","        VStack {","            Text(\"\\(model.viewDisplaysTotalCount)\")","            HStack {","                Button(\"+\") {","                    model.send(.userTappedIncrementButton)","                }","                Button(\"-\") {","                    model.send(.userTappedDecrementButton)","                }","            }","        }","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift","type":"file"},"doc://Statoscope/tutorials/Statoscope/01-04-Injection":{"type":"topic","url":"\/tutorials\/statoscope\/01-04-injection","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Learn how to easily design dependencies and inject them into your scopes. Dependency injection simplifies the structure of your code by externalizing the management of dependencies, making your code more modular, testable, and flexible. In this tutorial, we will demonstrate dependency injection using an example of a simple news feed application."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/Statoscope\/tutorials\/Statoscope\/01-04-Injection","role":"project","estimatedTime":"30min","title":"Dependency Injection","kind":"project"}}}